":[{"name":"Hammond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Almund</i>, in which Old English <i>Æthelmund</i> ‘noble protector’ and <i>Ealhmund</i> ‘temple protector’ have coalesced.","variant of   Allman   and   Allmand   both meaning ‘German’, assimilated by folk etymology to the vocabulary word denoting the tree."]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Breton, French, and English (Channel Islands): from the Breton, Old French, Middle English personal name <i>Hamon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. See also   Hammond  ."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): patronymic from the Norman personal name <i>Hamo</i>, <i>Hamon</i> (see   Hammond  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAmhsaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Amhsach</i>’ a byname meaning ‘mercenary soldier’ or ‘messenger’, from the adjective <i>amhasach</i> ‘aggressive’."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Hammond Jr was born in 1340, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Hammond Sr, was 30 and his mother, Grace Thomas, was 30. He married Princess Cycely Plantagenet Countess of Alycel about 1364, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 26 November 1389, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1340–26 November 1389":"1340–26. november 1389","1340–1389":"1340–1389","1340–1433":"1340–1433","1366–1440":"1366–1440","1366–1446":"1366–1446","1310–1340":"1310–1340","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","Jan 1366":"jaanuar 1366","1360":"1360","1446":"1446","26 November 1340":"26. november 1340","1433":"1433","1389":"1389","1366":"1366","Abt 1364":"umbes 1364","26 November 1389":"26. november 1389","1310":"1310","before 1340":"enne 1340","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lavenham, Babergh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Barnham, Suffolk, England":"Barnham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–26 November 1389":"1340–26. marraskuuta 1389","1340–1389":"1340–1389","1340–1433":"1340–1433","1366–1440":"1366–1440","1366–1446":"1366–1446","1310–1340":"1310–1340","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","Jan 1366":"tammikuu 1366","1360":"1360","1446":"1446","26 November 1340":"26. marraskuuta 1340","1433":"1433","1389":"1389","1366":"1366","Abt 1364":"noin 1364","26 November 1389":"26. marraskuuta 1389","1310":"1310","before 1340":"ennen vuotta 1340","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lavenham, Babergh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Barnham, Suffolk, England":"Barnham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"